Yvvid Concurrent Bike System – Design Overview

This project implements a non-blocking, concurrent bike dock system using a log-based (history-driven) approach. Instead of mutating shared state directly, all operations are recorded as actions in a global log, and the current system state is derived by replaying that log.

Core Idea: Log-Based State (Universal Construction)

At the heart of the system is a lock-free linked list (log) that stores all operations as Action<BikeDock> entries.

Each node represents an operation (e.g., MOVED_IN, MOVED_OUT, REPAIRED)
The system never directly modifies bike/dock state
Instead, it reconstructs state by scanning the log

This follows a universal construction pattern:

All threads agree on a single history of operations, and state is derived deterministically from that history.

Data Structures
log: Head of a lock-free linked list of actions
Node<T>: Represents each entry in the log (with atomic next pointer)
BikeDock: Combines a bike and its dock for logging
Set<BikeSolution>: Used to reconstruct current dock contents
How Operations Work

Every operation follows the same 3-step pattern:

1. Read (Reconstruct State)

Traverse the log and rebuild the relevant state:

Which bikes are in a dock
Whether a bike is available, repaired, etc.
2. Validate

Check if the operation is allowed:

Capacity constraints (dock not full)
Bike availability (e.g., must be READY)
Ownership (bike must exist in source dock)
3. Append to Log (Atomic)

Create a list of new actions and attempt to append them using compareAndSet:

If successful → operation commits
If it fails → retry (another thread modified the log)
⚙️ Key Methods
addBikes(dock, bikes)
Adds bikes to a dock if:
There is enough capacity
Bikes are in READY state
Appends IN_CIRCULATION actions
rideBikes(from, to, bikes)
Moves bikes between docks:
Validates bikes exist in source
Validates destination has space
Appends:
MOVED_OUT (from source)
MOVED_IN (to destination)
repairBikes(dock, bikes)
Marks bikes as repaired
Appends REPAIRED actions
rechargeBikes(dock, bikes)
Marks bikes as recharged
Appends RECHARGED actions
getBikes() / getBikes(dock)
Reconstructs system or dock-specific state by replaying the log
getStatusNEW(bike)
Scans the log to determine the current status of a bike
Latest relevant action determines status
Concurrency Model
Lock-free design using compareAndSet (CAS)
Multiple threads can:
Read the log concurrently
Attempt to append actions
If two threads conflict:
One succeeds
The other retries

This guarantees:

No locks (no blocking)
System-wide consistency
Thread safety
Important Notes / Limitations
Performance:
Every operation scans the entire log → can become slow as the log grows
Tail Handling:
Appending uses either:
log.next (empty log case)
tail.next (normal case)
Subtle Semantics:
Correct handling of actions like IN_CIRCULATION vs MOVED_IN is critical for consistency
Why This Approach?

This design is useful for:

Understanding lock-free data structures
Practicing linearizability
Learning how to build thread-safe systems without locks

It mirrors ideas used in:

Distributed systems logs
Event sourcing architectures
Summary
State is never stored directly — it’s derived from history
All operations are atomic log appends
Concurrency is handled via CAS + retries
The system is lock-free and linearizable
